<observation-set xmlns="http://vortex.cis.vtc.edu/xml/AOML_0.0"
  xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
  xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://vortex.cis.vtc.edu/xml/AOML_0.0 ../AOML/AOML.xsd">

  <location>
    <value>
      <lat-long-alt>+43.00-072.50+300</lat-long-alt>
    </value>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>Central Vermont, USA</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </location>
  <observer>Peter C. Chapin</observer>
  <notes>
    <xhtml:p>The temperature measurements shown here were all made with an inexpensive digital
      outdoor thermometer. They should not be considered particularly accurate.</xhtml:p>
  </notes>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-17T22:30:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-7.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>The sky is covered with a thin layer of clouds. The layer is thicker in some
            areas than others, but there are no completely clear spots.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>A handful of the brightest stars are visible through the clouds as fuzzy spots.
          No significant observing is possible.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>1</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-18T23:15:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-8.9</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>The sky is clear. There seems to be some haziness near the horizon but it is
            very minor.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>Conditions are good. The Beehive cluster is clearly visible. The Milky Way in
          Aug and Gem is not as obvious as ideal, however, so conditions could be better still.
          Nevertheless observing faint objects is very feasible.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>4</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-19T23:25:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-8.4</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>The sky is clear. Conditions are very similar to those of last
          night.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>Visibility is almost identical to last night's. Overall conditions are good but
          not excellent.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>4</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-20T23:45:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-1.1</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy. It was lightly snowing earlier in the
          evening.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-21T22:35:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">0.6</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and snowing.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-02-26T22:15:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-9.6</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is perfectly clear and fairly cold.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The conditions are good. There is a waxing crescent moon in the west. However,
          due to its relatively small size and its location the light does not cause a major
          problem. It would be possible to do deep sky observing over much of the sky.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>4</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-12T22:30:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-1.3</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and lightly snowing. There is a slight
          breeze.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-13T21:55:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-6.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is perfectly clear with a slight breeze. The temperature is rather
          cold.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The conditions are quite good tonight. The sky is clear and there is no moon.
          Many stars are visible; the Beehive Cluster in Cancer is particularly impressive. It
          would be a good night for deep sky objects.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>4</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-14T21:20:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">1.4</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy with light rain. It is also moderately
          windy.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-16T23:30:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-6.9</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and snowing.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-20T23:00:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">1.0</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and lightly sprinkling.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LST" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-03-21T22:40:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">-6.8</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is mostly cloudy and quite cold.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky to the east, and especially the northeast, is reasonably clear. Quite a
          few stars are visible in a small region there. However the rest of the sky is clouded
          over. Jupiter is visible through the clouds, but not much else.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>1</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-05-02T23:00:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">18.1</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and rather warm.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable. However, the large moon is still generating quite a
          bit of light.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-05-27T22:00:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is breezy tonight. The sky is partly cloudy with thin clouds covering
            perhaps half the sky.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The first quarter moon, bright planets, and some doubles could be readily
          observed. The clouds obscure significant portions of the sky but the regions between
          the clouds are reasonable (for a moonlite night).</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>3</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-05-30T23:30:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is cool and beautifully clear tonight.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is clear in all directions but the large moon is creating a lot of
          light.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>3</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-05-31T22:45:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is cool and mostly cloudy.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>Only about two or three stars are visible in the few clear patches between the
          clouds.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>1</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-07-01T22:10:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">16.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It rained earlier this evening. Now the sky is mostly obscured by clouds/fog.
            The humidity is very high.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>Only a handful of the brightest stars are visible.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>1</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-07-27T22:00:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">14.9</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It is completely cloudy and raining.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The sky is unobservable.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>0</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-08-01T21:35:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">20.8</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>Humidity is high; dew is heavy on the grass. There are some clouds but the
            sky is mostly clear. The air is very hazy, however.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The outlines of the constellations are visible, but no fainter stars. The sky
          is not yet completely dark.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>2</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-08-04T22:00:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">15.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>The sky is mostly clear but there is haze or fog in the hair. Dew is heavy on
            the grass.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>The basic constellations are visible, but faint stars are obscure.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>3</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT10M">
      <ISO>2004-08-17T23:05:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">15.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>There are considerable clouds to the north and west. However, the sky is
            rather clear to the east. The temperature is cool.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>Conditions are quite good in the clear regions of the sky. However, less than
          half the sky is clear and, in fact, significant parts are completely clouded
        over.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>3</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <localdatetime type="LDT" resolution="PT15M">
      <ISO>2004-09-07T05:45:00</ISO>
    </localdatetime>

    <skyconditions>
      <weather>
        <temperature>
          <value units="C">12.2</value>
        </temperature>
        <notes>
          <xhtml:p>It's a beautifully fresh morning. There are some clouds to the west but
            otherwise the sky is nicely clear.</xhtml:p>
        </notes>
      </weather>

      <notes>
        <xhtml:p>At this time there is considerably morning twilight. However, bright stars are
          visible as are Venus (of course) and Saturn. The crescent moon is well placed for
          observing. Conditions appear to be good.</xhtml:p>
      </notes>
      <rating>3</rating>
    </skyconditions>
  </observation>

</observation-set>
